data: {"type":"response.content_part.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_00532513722943b00169e450fa4890819390619139e041ab18","output_index":1,"part":{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"## The Monty Hall Problem (Step by Step)\n\n### 1) Setup\n- There are **3 doors**.\n- Behind **1 door** is a **prize**.\n- Behind the **2 other doors** is **nothing**.\n- You choose **1 door** (your initial choice).\n\n### 2) The host’s rule\nA host (Monty) knows where the prize is and:\n- Always opens a door you **did not** choose,\n- And always reveals a **goat** (a door without the prize),\n- Then offers you a choice: **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the other unopened door.\n\n### 3) Key idea: where the prize starts matters\nYour initial choice has two possibilities:\n\n#### Case A: You initially pick the winning door\n- Probability = **1/3**\n- If you picked correctly, then the remaining two doors both have goats.\n- Monty will open one of those goat doors.\n- If you **switch**, you lose (you switch to a goat).\n\n#### Case B: You initially pick a losing door\n- Probability = **2/3**\n- If you picked a goat, the prize is behind one of the two unchosen doors.\n- Monty must open **a goat** door among the two unchosen doors.\n- That means Monty is essentially “steering” you:\n  - The only unopened door left after he opens a goat door will be the **prize**.\n- If you **switch**, you win.\n\n### 4) Compare the strategies\n- **Always stay:**  \n  - You win only in Case A (probability **1/3**).\n- **Always switch:**  \n  - You win in Case B (probability **2/3**).\n\nSo:\n- **Switching wins with probability 2/3**\n- **Staying wins with probability 1/3**\n\n### 5) Why it feels surprising (intuition)\nAt first glance, after Monty opens a door, it’s tempting to think “2 doors left ⇒ 1/2 each.”  \nBut that ignores the fact that Monty’s choice is **not random**: he deliberately avoids revealing the prize. His action provides information, and that information shifts probability toward the strategy that uses it—**switching**.\n\n### 6) Quick numeric summary\n- Initial choice:\n  - Winning: **1/3**\n  - Losing: **2/3**\n- Monty’s reveal:\n  - Removes a goat door but does not change the initial probability split.\n- Therefore:\n  - Staying keeps **1/3**\n  - Switching captures the remaining **2/3**\n\nThat’s the core logic behind why **switching is better**."},"sequence_number":659}

